The execution result fed back to the LLM is actually a user message
(not an assistant message), with isExecutionResult: true. Its content
is a string of the form "Code execution result: <JSON>".

The JSON dictionary varies by outcome:

Success (with output):
  { success: true, prints, truncated, value, value_truncated, rounds_remaining }

Success (no output — treated as soft error):
  { success: true, no_output: true, hint: "Use print()...", rounds_remaining }

Error:
  { success: false, error_type, message, is_timeout, timeout_note, prints,
    truncated, hint (SyntaxError only), rounds_remaining }

Truncated LLM response (finish_reason === "length"):
  { success: false, error_type: "TruncatedResponse", message, rounds_remaining }
  Note: this is NOT a code execution response. The LLM's output was cut off
  mid-generation. The truncated code is not executed. The "Code execution
  result:" prefix in the feedback string is misleading here.

Key details:
- Built by buildExecutionFeedback() in src/lib/chat-orchestrator.ts (~line 412)
- TypeScript type is UserMessage from src/lib/chat-types.ts
  (role: "user", content: string, isExecutionResult: true,
   executionStatus: "ok" | "error")
- isExecutionResult and executionStatus are stripped before sending to the LLM
  by convertToLlmMessages() — the LLM only sees role and content
- On terminal success (no continue_thinking()), a second assistant message is
  also pushed containing user-visible text from collectTerminalOutput()
